Rounding to the nearest whole number is the same as rounding to the ones. The digit to the right determines how we will round.

If the digit is 5 or greater we round up otherwise we round down.

In this case we round down. Rounding down means the ones value stays the same and all numbers after it disappears.

Hence the answer is 3.

Rounding to the nearest whole number is the same as rounding to the ones. The digit to the right determines how we will round.

If the digit is 5 or greater we round up otherwise we round down.

In this case we round up. Rounding up means the ones value increases by 1 and all the numbers after it disappears.

Hence the answer is 7.

Expanded form is a way of writing a number that shows the sum of values of each digit of a number. First determine the place of the digit in the number.

Since 9 is in the tens place, we know that 9x10=90

Since 7 is in the ones place, we know that 7x1=7

Since 8 is in the tenths place, we know that 8x (1/10)=0.8

Since 9 is in the hundredths place, we know that 9x(1/100)=0.09

Hence the expanded form is 90 + 7 + 0.8 + 0.09

Expanded form is a way of writing a number that shows the sum of values of each digit of a number. First determine the place of the digit in the number.

Since 7 is in the tens place, we know that 7x10=70

Since 6 is in the ones place, we know that 6x1=6

Since 1 is in the tenths place, we know that 1x (1/10)=0.1

Since 2 is in the hundredths place, we know that 2x(1/100)=0.02

Hence the expanded form is 70+6+0.1+0.02
